Review: There are a ton of beautiful moments here, from the stunning music to more than a few heartbreaking sequences! I’m not sure this one will linger with me too much, though. As biopics go, I didn’t become quite as invested as I’d hoped for!

Movie: Harry Potter and the Half-Blood Prince
Harry Potter and the Order of the Phoenix

Review: Feeling a little ashamed that I had never seen this one either!

Absolutely not a Christmas Eve movie, but here we are! Not a ton of rewatch value with this one, but it’s pretty thrilling for one viewing. Even with so many moments played for the shock of it, Barry Keoghan plays what feels like the ultimate version of a character he’s been in several movies over the years, and he’s really great at it. Was going to give three stars, but I’m going to add another half for the very last scene, just because.

Ended up far more invested than I thought I might! It drew me into a world I know pretty much nothing about, and everyone’s performances were top notch. Didn’t think this was a movie I’d need tissues for either, but… bring them!

Seeing a new Miyazaki movie in the theater is an experience I’m glad to say I’ve had, just in case this is the last chance! Incredibly imaginative, and fills you with the kind of wonder movies used to provide when you were a kid. No one else is crafting stories like this.

Such a killer screenplay! Might need to watch it again to really grasp everything this brings to the table, but I was completely riveted for every moment on the first viewing. Everyone’s performance is so strong and distinct, and the entire story is so unnerving that the feeling sticks with you in the worst way.

Movie: The Hunger Games: The Ballad of Songbirds & Snakes

Review: This is easily going to join my list of best holiday movies, even if it’s maybe a little sadder than the rest! With all of its heavier moments, comedy still finds its way in so easily, and the film is baked in such a classic aesthetic that it earns a spot right alongside timeless favorites. Paul Giamatti is at his best, but Dominic Sessa and Da’Vine Joy Randolph really steal the show!

Movie: Billie Eilish: The World's a Little Blurry

Review: Not a ton of depth, but I’ll enjoy a grim Fincher story any time! Started strong for me, and tapered off a little towards the end. Fassbender is an ideal hitman, though!

I really wish this was anywhere as scary as playing the game! Definitely felt like Universal took the safest route possible making this, and besides the practical puppets being pretty cool, there’s nothing here that was enjoyable at all.
Yet another criminal hadn’t-seen-it-yet movie! I need to see this live.
Literally what else could you want from a classic horror movie?
Missing a few of my favorite songs, but I still feel like I got the full experience!
